body:
@piscisaureus I am trying to use node-gyp to build a C++ project (not make a node addon). node-gyp seemed to work just fine to build my a previous test `std::cout` console application.

I want to build that `main.cpp` file in the original issue message.

I am available in the #libuv IRC channel to chat as well.

@MadLittleMods 

You probably shouldn't be using node-gyp to build something that's not an addon (I think there are other tools on npm similar to node-gyp that support this use case). 

But if you insist, please try putting the full path to `uv.h` in the `#include` statement. I think node-gyp is setting up your include path such that main.cpp pick the wrong uv.h.

@piscisaureus I tried out [`gypjs`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/gypjs) and [`notnode-gyp`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/notnode-gyp). `gypjs` does the same thing as `node-gyp` but it is just a fork. `notnode-gyp` just doesn't work and errors out no matter what (problem with the package itself). Any suggestions on a alternative?

Back to `node-gyp`: 
I don't think it is making it to the `#include` directive point. If I use `
#include "uv/include/uv.h"` it has no difference (or even a invalid path `#include "foo/bar/uv.h"`). I think it is just stopping at trying to build libuv itself.

I am using the including it as a gyp module in binding.gyp `"uv/uv.gyp:libuv"`. Should I be using the `include` folder and `libuv.lib` file?
